nd literature, and show the potentials for a collaborative approach between literary scholars and linguists in understanding speech acts and reference; inference, cognitive and cultural background; rhetoric, styles of speaking and writing; as well as perspectives and genres.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCognitive grammar. 0aCreativity (Linguistics) 0aCreativity (Linguistics). 0aDiscourse analysis, Literary. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 4aDiskursanalyse. 4aGattungen. 4aLiteraturtheorie. 4aRhetorik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aDiscourse analysis.  aGenres.  aLiterary theory.  aRhetoric.1 aFludernik, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFludernik, Monika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGünthner, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHempfer, Klaus W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopper, Paul J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInda, Ana Renault, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacob, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacob, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKablitz, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKailuweit, Rolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinke, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOesterreicher, Wulf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPirlet, Caroline.1 aRaible, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRampton, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct